abstract: He fired Jeff Sessions. But a House Democratic majority prepares to pounce.
snippet: He fired Jeff Sessions. But a House Democratic majority prepares to pounce.
lead_paragraph: Frank Bruni: Ross, I hope you got more sleep than I did on Tuesday night. If not, this could be a very interesting conversation. We need to discuss the midterms and, of course, Jeff Sessions, but first, because I’m reeling, that White House news conference! President Trump really does possess mystical powers, because after years of beholding him, I remain full of wonder. I am still taken aback: the pettiness, the meanness, the extravagant flights of pure fantasy. Oh, and the epic self-congratulation. “A hot White House,” he called it. Is the A.C. broken? He said that he yearns to be boring. Well, then I yearn to be a credenza. Have you grown numb to it?

abstract: Or at least voted at equal rates.
snippet: Or at least voted at equal rates.
lead_paragraph: In Hawaii, Illinois and Vermont, voters who haven’t registered yet will be able to on Election Day, right before they cast a ballot. In Indiana, Mississippi and Georgia, the registration deadline is now weeks past, and registered voters who turn up will have to show a photo ID.

headline_print_headline: What Would Happen If Everyone Voted?

abstract: Party leaders worry that candidates for governor and Senate are in trouble in Michigan, Illinois, Minnesota, Pennsylvania and possibly Wisconsin, and that difficulties could spill into House races.
snippet: Party leaders worry that candidates for governor and Senate are in trouble in Michigan, Illinois, Minnesota, Pennsylvania and possibly Wisconsin, and that difficulties could spill into House races.
lead_paragraph: ANN ARBOR, Mich. — Republican leaders are increasingly worried that their candidates for governor and Senate are in political trouble across Michigan, Pennsylvania, Minnesota and other states that the party prizes, and that the difficulties could spill into House races that the G.O.P. needs to win in November to keep control of the chamber.

headline_main: G.O.P. Candidates Struggling in Key Battlegrounds, With House at Stake
headline_print_headline: Republicans See Trouble Spilling  Into House Races in Key States

abstract: Senator Kristen Gillibrand, a Democrat from New York, maintains that she is solely focused on her re-election. But her trips and campaign spending suggest otherwise.
snippet: Senator Kristen Gillibrand, a Democrat from New York, maintains that she is solely focused on her re-election. But her trips and campaign spending suggest otherwise.
lead_paragraph: CONCORD, N.H. — The last time that Senator Kirsten Gillibrand was on the ballot for re-election, she poured $8 million into a summer television-advertising spree en route to a landslide victory.

headline_main: Gillibrand’s (Lack of) Spending in 2018 Offers Hints of 2020
headline_print_headline: Gillibrand’s (Lack of) Spending on 2018 Re-election Offers Hints for 2020

abstract: In the On Politics newsletter, a record midterms for women sets the stage for a record presidential campaign; plus, a barrier-breaking candidate in Texas and a new poll in California.
snippet: In the On Politics newsletter, a record midterms for women sets the stage for a record presidential campaign; plus, a barrier-breaking candidate in Texas and a new poll in California.
lead_paragraph: Hi. Welcome to On Politics, your guide to the day in national politics. I’m Lisa Lerer, your host.

headline_main: Democrats, Looking Ahead to 2020, See a Future That Is Female

abstract: “It’s not going to be just one woman running,” said Kirsten Gillibrand, one of three senators who positioned themselves this week as potential presidential candidates in 2020.
snippet: “It’s not going to be just one woman running,” said Kirsten Gillibrand, one of three senators who positioned themselves this week as potential presidential candidates in 2020.
lead_paragraph: GREENVILLE, S.C. — Three prominent female Democrats all but openly began running for president this week, taking their most active steps yet to challenge President Trump and claim leadership of a movement of moderate and liberal women that has come to define their party during the 2018 elections.
